Question1

Function

same_birth<-function(n){
birthdays = sample(1:365, n, replace = TRUE)
  any(duplicated(birthdays))
}

Simulation

set.seed(36501)  

n_values <- 2:50 
simulations <- 10000 
probabilities <- sapply(n_values, function(n) {
  mean(replicate(simulations, same_birth(n)))
})

Plot

plot(n_values, probabilities, type = "b", pch = 19, col = "blue",
     xlab = "Group Size (n)",
     ylab = "Probability of Shared Birthday",
     main = "Birthday Paradox Simulation")

abline(h = 0.5, col = "red", lty = 2)

Question2

Data

set.seed(36501)

n <- 30
sigma <- 5
mu_values <- 0:6
n_sim <- 5000
simulate_mu <- function(mu) {
  replicate(n_sim, {
    x <- rnorm(n, mean = mu, sd = sigma)
    test <- t.test(x, mu = 0)
    tibble(
      mu_true = mu,
      mu_hat = mean(x),
      p_value = test$p.value
    )
  }, simplify = FALSE) |> bind_rows()
}

results <- map_df(mu_values, simulate_mu)

results <- results %>%
  mutate(reject = p_value < 0.05)
results

Plot1

power_summary <- results %>%
  group_by(mu_true) %>%
  summarize(power = mean(reject))

ggplot(power_summary, aes(x = mu_true, y = power)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", linewidth = 1.2) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(
    x = "True mean ()",
    y = "Proportion of rejections (Power)",
    title = "Power of one-sample t-test vs Effect Size"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

plot2

 mu_summary <- results %>%
  group_by(mu_true) %>%
  summarize(
    avg_mu_hat_all = mean(mu_hat),
    avg_mu_hat_reject = mean(mu_hat[reject])
  )

ggplot(mu_summary, aes(x = mu_true)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = avg_mu_hat_all, color = "All samples"), linewidth = 1.2) +
  geom_point(aes(y = avg_mu_hat_all, color = "All samples")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = avg_mu_hat_reject, color = "Rejected only"), linewidth = 1.2, linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_point(aes(y = avg_mu_hat_reject, color = "Rejected only")) +
  labs(
    x = "True mean ()",
    y = "Average estimate ()",
    title = "Average estimates across all samples vs rejected samples",
    color = ""
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

AnsNo, the sample average of $$ across tests for which the null was rejected is not approximately equal to the true value of \(\mu\), especially when the true effect size is small.

This happens because we are conditioning on rejection of the null hypothesis (i.e.,<0.05). When the true mean \(\mu\) is close to 0, only those samples that happened by random chance to produce unusually large sample means will yield significant results. As a result, the average of $$ among the significant samples is biased upward relative to the true $$.

As the true effect size increases and the tests power approaches 1, this selection bias disappears almost all samples are significant, and the conditional average of $$ converges to the true value.

  mutate(
    unsolved = if_else(

city_summary <- homicide_data %>%
  group_by(city_state) %>%
  summarize(
    total = n(),
    unsolved = sum(unsolved),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

baltimore <- city_summary %>%
  filter(city_state == "MD, Baltimore")

baltimore_test <- prop.test(
  x = baltimore$unsolved,
  n = baltimore$total
)

baltimore_result <- tidy(baltimore_test)

Every City

city_results <- city_summary %>%
  mutate(
    test = map2(unsolved, total, ~ prop.test(.x, .y) %>% tidy())
  ) %>%
  unnest(test) %>%
  select(city_state, estimate, conf.low, conf.high, total) %>%
  arrange(desc(estimate))
